        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Alaaraaf i've heard both.  some people have problems up the ass, others they run smooth.  </P><P>did you build your own computer or buy it?  have you added any hardware that didn't originally come with it?</P><P>a lot of companies get their own personalized versions of windows which will run better then one you build yourself since everything was setup specifically for those devices.  get the newest drivers and you can have problems (i've often gone back to original drivers i got because they ran better then the newer ones).</P><P>so if you have a prebuilt computer from a company and you haven't added anything (newer drivers, hardware, etc...) then you would probably have less trouble then someone who builds their own.  </P><P>personally, i build my own.  so i prefer a platform that doesn't mind me screwing with it...and for all of 98's faults, it doesn't give 2 shits what i do to it :).  a few systems that i've had to troubleshoot that ran XP (either at work or for friends) have driven me insane.  if XP doesn't automatically set it up properly, it really is quite annoying to do so manually.  i was working on some of the first wave release XP (aka: beta, you think VI is bad?) and it wouldn't let me add a protocol unless i went through their little "wizard".  arrr, working on XP annoys me, hehe.</P><P><a href="http://www.theinverselogic.com/" target="_blank"><BR>Abillister "Monkey" Abu<BR>Inverse Logic</a></font></td>
